Administration of VAT in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany
Control audit report
Preface
Taxes are the most important source of revenue for public budgets.
A focus of the work of the sais should therefore be on the audit of this area.
This applies in particular to VAT fraud.
This alone causes annual tax losses in the European Union of an estimated 100 billion Euro1.
Already in the VI EUROSAI Congress 2005 in Bonn, the participants pointed to the need for enhanced cooperation.
This allows the courts of auditors, for example, to exchange audit approaches and optimize audit practice.
VAT is particularly suitable for cooperation as it is harmonised within the European Union.
In 2006, the sais of both states examined for the first time in parallel in the field of VAT.
The corresponding audit report was published in 2008.
As VAT fraud is a widespread phenomenon in the European Union, there is a need for close cooperation between the courts of auditors. This allows a comprehensive assessment to be made as to whether the measures taken are likely to counter the VAT fraud effectively.
The two SAIs have decided to continue their cooperation and carried out a second parallel test. Administration of value added tax in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany report on the control test
1. Introduction
Examination number: (CZ) 09/11 (D) VIII 2 - 2009 - 0892
Subject of audit: (CZ) administration of the USt (D) bilateral audit with the court of Auditors of the Czech Republic (hereinafter NKÚ), audit
Audit objective:
(CZ) Tested the USt-management and the treatment of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic (hereafter CZ) and the Federal Republic of Germany (hereinafter Germany). In addition, the procedures applied by the tax authorities in the case of intergovernmental assistance should be examined.
(D) the audit should evaluate how the financial administration has implemented the recommendations made by the sais.
In addition, further examination fields linked to the USt should be edited.
The findings made here should be compared to determine whether the tax procedures can be optimized.
Examination period of the years 2006 to 2008, including relevant information from the period prior to the audit period up to the completion of the test.
2. What do you mean? Summary of results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The audit offices of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany have agreed to carry out a control audit for the administration of the VAT.
In the previous parallel examination, they had detected suspicions of intra-community turnover,
which allowed a further examination to be made appropriate.
On the basis of the audit findings, the two sais made recommendations on the management of the VAT.
The purpose of the audit was to evaluate how these recommendations were implemented. In addition, the suspected cases should be investigated.
The audit also dealt with other issues. These included selected cases of high-risk intra-community transactions, Mutual Administrative Assistance in the recovery of VAT claims and VAT checks on large enterprises.
The court of Auditors has established:
1. 1. 1. Recommendations made on the basis of the previous review
* Recommendation 1: the arrangements for the registration of taxpayers should be harmonised within the EU
At the first examination, the sais compared the VAT registration procedures in the two states and found differences that caused problems.
The sais therefore recommended harmonising the registration of taxpayers within the EU.
This has also been taken up at EU level.
The draft amendment to council regulation no 1798/2003 provides for the extension of the existing databases in the EU, including a database with the VAT identification number.
The draft also provided for common rules for the registration of taxpayers and their possible cancellation.
The sais expected member states to agree on appropriate arrangements to remove unreliable traders from the VAT System as early as possible, in line with their policy decision.
The member states reached political agreement in ECOFIN on the last draft.
The common rules referred to above are no longer included. The two sais regret this.
They continue to believe that such rules are important in order to prevent VAT fraud.
* Recommendation 2: monthly submission of summary reports as a result of the first audit, sais recommended to member states that the summary reports (CA) should be submitted monthly in future.
The amounts of intra-community transactions could then be reviewed more closely.
With the Directive 2008/117/EC Amending Directive 2006/112/EC on the common system of value added tax to combat tax evasion connected with intra-community transactions and the deadline for the submission of the ZM has been reduced to one month.
In the Czech Republic, this requirement was met by a decision taken on 1 January 2007. The amendment to the USt Act, which entered into force on 19 January 2010, was implemented.
In Germany, the implementation took place only on 1 January 2007. It entered into force on 19 July 2010. It has therefore not transposed the obligation to submit the CTM monthly into national law within the prescribed period.
* Recommendation 3: Reconciliation of pre-VAT and CTM data in Germany for more reliable MIAS data and proposal to review the consolidation of pre-VAT and CTM procedures the German financial administration has taken up the recommendation issued by the federal accounting court and set up a working group to develop possible solutions.
The work has not yet been completed.
The federal accounting court will monitor further developments.
* Recommendation 4: exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level during the first audit, the two sais agreed that an effective risk management system cannot be developed by one member state alone.
Successful criteria and elements or approaches of a risk management system must be exchanged and implemented in each EU member state.
If this is not done, fraudsters will focus on the member state with the weakest risk management system.
The SAIs found that the two States apply different risk management systems which have both Strengths and weaknesses.
The NKU examined the System of information exchange within the EU - EUROCANET, as the Federal court of audit focused on the German participation in the "platform for risk management".
2. What do you mean? Inspection of selected intra-community transactions
In the first audit, the sais had jointly examined transactions for which it was doubtful whether they had actually been exported or which had been declared differently by the taxable persons of the two states in the VAT declarations (or VAT declarations) or ZM.
The sais selected nine cases of intra-community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for the control check.
The examinations by the tax offices (FÄ) of both states have not yet been completed at the end of the first parallel examination.
The audit showed that the tax procedures for these selected revenues have now been completed. The respective tax authorities had taken appropriate measures (including subsequent VAT assessments or the prevention of input Tax refunds).
3. 3. 4. Examination of selected, particularly risky intra-community transactions
The audit also included highly risky intra-community transactions between EU taxpayers covered by the EUROCANET System.
The purpose of EUROCANET is to identify risk-prone taxpayers.
Member states may participate in this System on a voluntary basis.
The CZ is an active Participant in EUROCANET. Germany has a passive Status, i.e. it does not participate in the exchange of data within the framework of EUROCANET.
From the point of view of an active participating state, it is unsatisfactory that other member states refuse to participate actively.
As a result, no information could be obtained about which suppliers with German VAT ID would have been classified as highly risky cases.
The NKU noted both normal business transactions and those with a suspicion of VAT fraud, including carousel fraud, in the selected sales.
FÄ was only able to audit high-risk sales to a limited extent. This was particularly the case with so-called "Missing Traders", whereby an examination of the documents alone is hardly sufficient to be able to prove the taxable fraud.
If there is a suspicion of carousel fraud in the case of imports and exports
it is recommended that Customs and tax authorities work more closely together to monitor the identity of the goods and their actual transport routes within the EU to the final customer.
Germany and a number of other countries have rejected an active participation in EUROCANET, as they do not have a sufficient legal basis.
The Bundesrechnungshof found that the German tax administration uses other instruments to identify high-risk taxpayers.
Nevertheless, there is a need for communication and exchange of experience between all EU member States.
The EU Council agreed on a draft regulation,
by the EUROFISC was created.
The experience gained so far with EUROCANET should be integrated into the planned network for combating VAT fraud.
4.4. 4.Mutual assistance in the recovery of claims
Intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims is subject to the same European legislation in all member states.
Therefore, requests for intergovernmental assistance in the recovery of claims in the CZ and Germany are dealt with in the same way.
Federal Court of accounts and NKU compared the statistics submitted by both member states to the European Commission for the years 2006 to 2008.
These statistics contained inconsistencies.
The two sais consider that a renewed discussion on statistics at EU level is useful in order to avoid any remaining inconsistencies in the future.
If this is not the case, the statistics cannot be used appropriately for comparisons.
In addition, the statistics should contain more information about the USt.
An analysis of detailed data can make it easier for the Commission to support the member States in their efforts to combat VAT fraud.
Both sais consider that member states with a low recovery rate should endeavour to reach at least the average recovery rate.
The commission should support the member states in this regard if this is desired.
5. What do you mean? VAT inspection for large enterprises
The sais analysed the legal situation with regard to the VAT audit for large companies in both states.
In addition, they collected with a questionnaire information from the tax administrations, which they considered important in this context.
It became clear that the Situation was different in both states.
The CZ has a system for the selection of risky cases that involves a large amount of relevant data (including information on VAT checks, data from balance sheets and profit and loss accounts).
As a result, the VAT control can be effectively controlled and analysed.
A special tax office for large enterprises is to be established in 2012.
There is no comparable System in Germany. This makes it difficult to control and Analyse the VAT control as a whole.
The German financial administration focuses more on the selection of relevant individual cases and is based on data from the VAT returns or VAT declarations and the ZM.
Various risk management components, which are to be improved, support the evaluation of these data.
