4. 4. 4. Audit of the management of VAT in selected areas
4.1 implementation of recommendations from the first joint examination
4.1.1 implementation of recommendations in the Czech Republic
Recommendation 1
Harmonisation of the conditions for registration of taxpayers within the EU supported
on the results of the first audit, the Czech court of Auditors has recommended adjusting the requirements for VAT registration and introducing new rules for the cancellation of registration in the CZ.
These amended rules should reduce the risk of possible tax evasion more effectively.
In certain cases, it was found that the FÄ did not delete the VAT registration of taxable persons if they did not comply with their obligations under Czech law no 235/2004 (hereinafter referred to as the "VAT law").
To date, the Czech Ministry of Finance has not submitted any amendments to oblige the FA to cancel if taxpayers repeatedly do not submit VAT returns.
Under the Czech VAT Act, the FA may cancel the registration of a Taxable Person of its own motion if: a) the taxable person has not made any transactions for 12 consecutive months and has not informed the FA of the reasons for such transactions; b) the taxable person has not fulfilled its obligations under the VAT Act; c) the taxable person no longer
The first examination had shown that, due to the existing legal situation, the FA Prague 1 was able to register the VAT registration of "foreign taxpayers"3 with effect from December 31, 2012. In the following calendar year, if they were not obliged to register and pay VAT in the current calendar year.
The FA Prague 1 often failed to remove the VAT registration of these taxpayers because the relevant determination of the time limit could not be properly implemented in practice.
The Problem was solved by the amendment of the USt Act, which came into force on 1 January 2012. It entered into force on January 22, 2009.
Accordingly, the FA is entitled to cancel the registration of a foreign taxable person who has not supplied taxable or exempt supplies of goods or services in the preceding calendar year with the right to deduct input tax.
Recommendation 2
Monthly submission of the ZM
On the basis of the initial audit, the sais had recommended that the monthly levy on ZM be introduced.
The council directive, which reduced the rate of levy on the CTM to one month, was amended in the CZ by the council decision of 1 January 2002 (OJ L 331, 31.12.2002, P. 1). The VAT Act entered into force on January 22, 2010.
The ZM must now be submitted electronically.
In addition, a CTM must be provided if Services whose place of performance is to be determined in accordance with § 9 (1) VAT Act are provided for a person registered as a taxable person in another member state.
The condition is that the recipient is obliged to declare and pay the VAT for these services. This obligation arises from Directive 2008/8/EC Amending Directive 2006/112/EC as regards the place of supply of services.
Recommendation 3
Comparison of the data from the VAT pre-declarations and the ZM to increase the reliability of the MIAS data this recommendation was related to the German tax administration.
In its Atis4 System, the Czech tax administration automatically compares the data on intra-community transactions from the VAT declarations and the CTM.
Recommendation 4
Exchange of successful criteria, components or approaches for a risk management system at EU level
The proper collection of VAT is a prerequisite for the smooth Functioning of the EU internal market.
Therefore, the fight against VAT fraud is of primary interest and has received considerable attention in recent years.
The importance of this is evidenced, among other things, by an investigation published by the European Commission in October 2009.
In this report, an external expert estimated the VAT loss for the 25 member states between 2000 and 2006. After analysis of the available data, the tax loss for the above period was estimated at EUR 90 to 113 billion. This was based on the fact that the EU-25 lost an average of 12% of their turnover taxes each year.
The estimated zero tax loss for the CZ was 18% in 2006.
The first audit found that a member state alone cannot develop an effective risk management system (RMS).
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each member state.
Based on the RMS of the Czech court of auditors has audited the System for the exchange of information within the EU (EUROCANET).
For this purpose, intra-community transactions carried out by taxpayers within the EU and recorded in EUROCANET were selected (see Chapter 4.3).
The EUROFISC network aims to optimise mutual assistance in tax matters and to combat VAT fraud more effectively. Cooperation between competent authorities is to be improved in order to identify fraud as early as possible.
Later EUROFISC could be used as a tool to assess the risk potential of intra-community sales.
The ECOFIN Council6 has already approved EUROFISC on 7 July. It was endorsed by the European Parliament on 10 October 2008 and adopted at the same time the principles for the functioning of the system.
As a model for EUROFISC, EUROCANET, which has been developed by the Belgian tax administration, in cooperation with the other member States and with the support of the European Commission and of OLAF7.
The purpose of the system is to detect risky transactions and to identify entrepreneurs involved in the organised VAT fraud.
