4.2 verification of selected intra-community transactions
In the first examination, transactions were examined jointly for which there were doubts as to whether they had actually been exported or whether there were any inconsistencies in the taxable persons ' declarations in both member states.
The two sais selected nine cases of intra-community deliveries of goods between the CZ and Germany for which the tax examination by the FAI of the member state concerned had not yet been completed at the time of the previous joint examination.
One)
In the first quarter of 2005, a Czech Taxable Person acquired goods worth 22 686 euros from a German taxable person.
The Czech taxpayer did not declare the acquisition in its VAT declaration,since Germany had no VAT identification number but only a tax number for domestic transactions during the period.
By means of international administrative assistance in accordance with the Council regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the competent Czech FA had received information that according to German VAT law, the supplier of intra-community Goods, no VAT identification number is needed to ensure the tax exemption of intra-community deliveries of goods.
The audit carried out by the Czech court of auditors showed that - according to the audit by the Czech FA - the Czech taxpayer submitted an additional VAT declaration declaring the acquisition of goods in the above value and at the same time claiming his right to deduct input tax in the same amount.
Two)
In the fourth quarter of 2004, a Czech taxable person is expected to have purchased from a German taxable person worth EUR 12 561.
However, he stated that he had not purchased the goods and therefore did not declare in his VAT declaration.
The German tax administration, relying on a provision of the Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, refused to deal with the request because the turnover linked to the acquisition did not exceed the threshold of 15 000 euros.
As the Czech FA was unable to obtain any documents, the tax audit remained unprofit and the original tax assessment remained in place.
The audit carried out by the Czech court of auditors showed that the Czech FA received two spontaneous reports from Germany in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, according to which the German taxable person had invoiced the delivery of the goods to a Slovak addressee.
The Czech Taxpayer acquired Goods from the Slovak Taxable persons and for the acquisition in its regular VAT return for the month of October 2004.
Three)
A Czech taxable person is expected to have purchased a car worth 48 500 euros from a German taxable person in the fourth quarter of 2004.
However, it did not declare an intra-community acquisition.
In addition, he had not issued a VAT declaration since August 2004. For this reason, the FA fixed the VAT for the quarter in question at CZK 0.
On the basis of information received from Germany in the course of the international exchange of information pursuant to Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, the FA requested the taxpayer to submit a subsequent tax return in March 2007, but the taxpayer failed to do so.
The audit found that the FA had undertaken further audit procedures in this tax case in 2007. It was found that the car had been sold by the Taxpayer to a used car dealer in the CZ.
The Czech FA for the tax period of December, 2004 an assessment and imposed additional taxes in the amount of 295 379 CZK for the acquisition of Goods from another member state and their re-sale.
The competent Czech court decided to initiate insolvency proceedings on the assets of the Czech taxpayer; an insolvency administrator was appointed.
In the absence of significant assets, the outstanding tax liability is likely to be irrecoverable.
Four)
A Czech taxable person is expected to have delivered new vehicles (passenger cars) to Germany in the fourth quarter of 2004 and the first quarter of 2005 for a total value of EUR 198 167.
In response to a request for information under Council Regulation (EC) 1798/2003, it was stated that the German taxpayer was subject to a tax penalty in Germany.
The audit carried out by the Federal Court of auditors showed that, after the proceedings had been completed, there was evidence that the German taxpayer was involved in fraud.
The intra-community acquisition of goods was subject to taxation in the amount of 182 424 Euro (for 2004) and 369 690 Euro (for 2005).
